Position Parameter

When you’re working with timelines in GSAP, controlling when things happen is just as important as what happens. This lesson is all about mastering timing - setting up precise sequences and creating smooth overlaps that make your animations feel fluid and natural.

This is where the Position Parameter comes in. It’s that special third argument that orchestrates the flow of your timeline!

What is the Position Parameter?

The position parameter is used to tell GSAP:

Start this animation at this exact time on the timeline.

  • It works with .to(), .from(), .fromTo(), and more.
  • It’s incredibly flexible - letting you set exact start times, create gaps, overlap tweens, or even use labels!

We'll explore everything in deeply about Position Parameter in this lesson.

Absolute vs Relative Timings

Let's start with Absolute and Relative Timing. In a GSAP timeline, every animation (tween) you add has a start time.

  • By default, tweens are added one after another (sequentially).
  • But you can also control exactly when they start, using absolute or relative timings.

📌 Absolute Timings

Think of this as setting the exact timestamp for when a tween starts in the timeline.

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 1 }, 0); // starts at 0s
tl.to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, 2); // starts at 2s

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 1 }, 0); // starts at 0s
tl.to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, 2); // starts at 2s

The third parameter (like 0 or 2 above) is the absolute time (in seconds).

📌 Relative Timings

Instead of setting an exact time, you can tell GSAP to start a tween relative to the end of the previous tween.

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 1 }).to(
".circle",
{ y: 300, duration: 1 },
"+=3"
); // starts 3s after .box finishes

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl
.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 1 })
.to(
  ".circle",
  { y: 300, duration: 1 },
  "+=3"
); // starts 3s after .box finishes
  • +=3 means start 3 seconds later.
  • You can also use -=3 to start 3 seconds earlier.
Insight

They make it super easy to tweak the rhythm of your animation without reworking everything.

Overlapping Animations with Negative Relative Position

You’ve already seen how the Position Parameter helps you control when animations happen. But sometimes, you don’t want animations to just line up one after another - you want them to overlap and create smoother transitions.

That’s where negative relative positions come in!

Learning

A negative relative value like -=0.5 tells GSAP:

👉 Start this tween before the previous one ends.

✅ It’s the secret to seamless overlaps that make Awwwards-winning animations feel polished and professional.

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // .box moves to the right in 2s
.to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "-=0.5"); // .circle moves down, starts 0.5s before .box ends

Result 

import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // .box moves to the right in 2s
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "-=0.5"); // .circle moves down, starts 0.5s before .box ends
  • The first tween .box starts at 0s and runs for 2 seconds.
  • The second tween .circle normally would start at 2s (right after .box finishes).
  • But with "-=0.5", it actually starts 0.5s before .box ends - so it begins at 1.5s!

Relative to Others – Precise Timeline Control

When you’re building complex animations, it’s not always enough to say start 2 seconds in or start 1 second later. Sometimes you want to anchor an animation directly to another - no guesswork, no math.

That’s where the Relative to Others position parameter comes in!

What is Relative to Others ?

In GSAP, "<" and ">" are special symbols that reference the previous tween in the timeline:

Symbol Meaning
"<" Start at the start of the previous tween.
">" Start at the end of the previous tween.

You can combine them with offsets to fine-tune your timing even more!

Using "<" - Start at Previous Tween’s Start

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // box animates for 2s
.to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "<"); // circle starts at same time as box

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // box animates for 2s
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "<"); // circle starts at same time as box

Here, the circle starts exactly when the box starts - perfect for synchronized animations!

Using ">" - Start at Previous Tween’s End

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // box animates for 2s
.to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, ">"); // circle starts when box ends

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }) // box animates for 2s
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, ">"); // circle starts when box ends

Here, the circle waits until the box is done before starting - perfect for sequential, clean transitions!

Fine-tuning with Offsets

What if you want an animation to start a bit after or a bit before the start or end of the previous tween? You can add offsets to these relative pointers.

Example: "<+=0.5" - 0.5 Seconds After Previous Start

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }).to(
".circle",
{ y: 300, duration: 1 },
"<+=0.5"
); // starts 0.5s after box starts

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 })
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "<+=0.5"); // starts 0.5s after box starts
  • The circle starts 0.5 seconds after the box animation begins.
  • Great for slight overlaps!
Symbol What it does
"<" Starts at the previous tween’s start.
">" Starts at the previous tween’s end.
"<+=0.5" Starts 0.5s after the previous tween’s start.

Percentage-based values

And here’s an advanced technique you might not know about yet - percentage-based position values!

In GSAP 3.7 and later, you can use percentages in your position parameter to base offsets on the total duration of the tween being inserted or the previous tween.

Percentage Overlap

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }).to(
".circle",
{ y: 300, duration: 1 },
"-=25%"
); // starts 25% of circle's duration before box ends

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 })
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "-=25%"); // starts 25% of circle's duration before box ends

✅ -=25% means the circle animation will start 25% of its own duration earlier — perfect for subtle overlaps!

Percentage from Previous Animation

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 }).to(
".circle",
{ y: 300, duration: 1 },
"<25%"
); // starts 25% into the box animation

Result 

const tl = gsap.timeline();

tl.to(".box", { x: 300, duration: 2 })
  .to(".circle", { y: 300, duration: 1 }, "<25%"); // starts 25% into the box animation

✅ <25% means the circle animation starts 25% into the previous animation’s duration.

So if you’re working on a timeline that might change, percentage-based values are a super handy way to keep things smooth and in sync!

🏁 Conclusion

And there you have it! The Position Parameter is your key to choreographing animations with total precision and style.

  • Use absolute timings for exact control.
  • Use relative and negative relative timings for gaps and overlaps.
  • Use "<", ">", and "<+=0.5" to sync everything perfectly.

Keep experimenting - these tools will transform your animations from simple to spectacular!
